+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01MR2sGrzhRS914JweUUkC3w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me think through the architecture using a \"pivot\" perspective — instead of the naive approach of storing full document snapshots per branch, let me think about what's truly central: the **three-way merge** is the hardest part, and the data model should be designed to make that easy. The pivot insight is: branches need to know their fork point (common ancestor) to make three-way merge work. So I'll track a \"snapshot\" at each branch creation point and use that as the base for merging.\n\nKey design decisions:\n1. Each branch stores its own map of documents (deep-cloned on fork).\n2. When a branch is created, I record the fork point — a snapshot of document states at that moment — which serves as the common ancestor for three-way merge.\n3. The merge algorithm walks all documents that exist in base/ours/theirs, does deep field-by-field comparison, and produces conflicts at the leaf level.\n\nLet me implement this now."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":262,"cache_read_input_tokens":20167,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":262},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8f4d5b5e-ec15-4f5c-96f6-a6925c707f94","uuid":"3303bb09-432b-49a4-844b-77ff53979187"}
